WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.280 --> 00:00:18.860
Hi, and welcome to a very special Designing Open Democracy Podcast on a talk held in March 2020 with Antony McMullen, where he will talk about how we can go beyond just corporate social responsibilities towards a fundamentally more democratic economic and corporate structure.

2
00:00:18.860 --> 00:00:28.440
Given the situation around the world with the 2020 global pandemic, this talk will be a little bit different given the social distancing requirements in Australia at the time of the recording.

3
00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:37.900
This was organized and ran by Alexa Pandeschi, who you will be quite familiar with our first podcast episode on Trust as a Concept.

4
00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:40.280
I'll definitely recommend you to check it out as well.

5
00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:45.500
It's a deep discussion on to the nature of trust and how it underpins a society.

6
00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:57.780
Anyhow, our main guest speaker Antony McMullen is a co-operative entrepreneur based in Melbourne, Australia and is an expert in co-operative development, policy and enterprises for the common good.

7
00:00:57.780 --> 00:01:07.460
As co-founder of Co-operative Bonds, his consultancy specializes in offering expert advice and support to help build and grow many other co-operatives.

8
00:01:07.460 --> 00:01:15.540
Later in this episode, we will have a panel where we will be joined by Sean and Ayn from Earthworkers and Behive respectively.

9
00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:24.480
But let's start with Antony's introduction right at the point where we finally got the video conferencing feed to be stable enough for the event to officially start.

10
00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:26.860
Enjoy!

11
00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:30.960
So, lots of people will be having a crash course of what it's like to be e-working.

12
00:01:31.380 --> 00:01:33.420
Yeah, yeah, we're all learning together.

13
00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:37.560
Wearing my son's gamer headphones in the kind of middle lounge room of the house.

14
00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:41.140
And I think we've all just got these makeshift set ups.

15
00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:44.440
I actually prefer to work outside of home.

16
00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:50.320
And one of the cooperatives I'm involved with is as a shared office space in the center of the CBD.

17
00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:52.200
So I love being able to have home for home.

18
00:01:52.200 --> 00:02:06.040
And then when I'm doing project work, going to a little cooperative space in the city, which with quite a reasonable cost because we've come together as a co-operative and separate work from home in that way.

19
00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:08.500
So anyway, so I'll get back to my presentation.

20
00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:20.300
I think I'll probably quickly and I might gloss over a few parts because I think the conversation with people that are online and hearing from fellow panel members will be really rewarding, I think.

21
00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:22.180
So just what is a co-op?

22
00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:24.960
It's an autonomous association.

23
00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:29.960
It should be doing what its members feel is the best thing for them to do.

24
00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:34.680
That means that it shouldn't be controlled by any government or outside entity.

25
00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:36.340
It's an association of persons.

26
00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:41.080
Generally, that's people like you and me, but it can be, in some cases, small businesses.

27
00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:46.920
I did some work with a group of stonemasons and they all had their own little separate owner operated business.

28
00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:48.740
They wanted to come together as a co-operative.

29
00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:57.760
So the businesses, little owner operated businesses were the members rather than them as actual persons like you and me.

30
00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:08.540
So people come together voluntarily to meet their common economic, social and cultural needs and aspirations through a jointly owned and democratically controlled enterprise.

31
00:03:08.540 --> 00:03:12.700
So essentially, it's a democratically controlled and owned business.

32
00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:16.940
The three key parts of this are social good.

33
00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:19.260
So you're building social good in the community.

34
00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:24.880
You're doing something good for yourselves as members and the border community is benefiting.

35
00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:28.900
There's an economic good because you're democratizing the economy.

36
00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:32.940
You're sharing the rewards for effort through broadening our ownership.

37
00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:44.360
And lastly, there's a cultural effect where people are coming together to work together in new ways and they're building a different kind of culture and are building a culture of relationship between each other.

38
00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:48.820
So often when we think of democracy, we just think of the government, think of elections.

39
00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:57.200
But the cultural piece is actually making democracy work for you and I through these enterprises that we build and operate together.

40
00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:59.960
Co-operatives have a set of ethics and values.

41
00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:03.460
Co-operative members should be honest and open with each other.

42
00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:08.820
They should care for each other and also have an eye for being socially responsible.

43
00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:17.800
And co-operatives also are based on the values of self-help and self-responsibility, democracy, equality, equity and solidarity.

44
00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:23.160
And I often think that the two balancing co-operative values are self-responsibility.

45
00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:26.080
Yep, I'm going to do something about this situation.

46
00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:28.800
Backed into a corner here, what are we going to do?

47
00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:34.700
And solidarity, a sense of connection between the people who are part of a co-operative.

48
00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:36.940
There's seven co-operative principles.

49
00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:39.540
Concern for the community being key.

50
00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:42.560
Members putting in to build the co-operative and getting out.

51
00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:48.680
So it's economic participation, democracy, autonomy, I mentioned, voluntary and open membership.

52
00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:56.280
So as long as you are able to fulfill the obligations of membership, membership is open.

53
00:04:56.280 --> 00:05:02.800
Co-ops should be cooperating amongst each other and also focusing on education and development.

54
00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:18.460
That co-ops themselves, being a part of a co-op is a very deep learning experience because you're learning, you're not just turning up to, in the case of a worker co-op, you're not just turning up to work, actually learning about how this business works overall.

55
00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:22.600
So you're doing the stuff, but you're knowing how to read financial statements and other things.

56
00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:29.160
That's why education and development is really important for all members so they can understand the business as a whole.

57
00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:33.300
So a cooperative member, according to Tim Maseroll, wears four hats.

58
00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:38.580
Tim Maseroll being an academic in this area from the University of Western Australia.

59
00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:43.800
They can be a patron, so they can be, for example, a customer or they can be a worker.

60
00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:47.260
So they're getting something as part of that relationship.

61
00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:51.480
They're an owner, so they own this business together.

62
00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:57.980
They're an investor, they're putting in time and money, and they're hoping to get some reward for themselves and for the broader community.

63
00:05:57.980 --> 00:06:04.340
The last hat is being a community member, having a view for the good of the community as a whole.

64
00:06:04.340 --> 00:06:05.620
Different types of co-ops.

65
00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:13.200
There's consumer co-ops, so it might be a bookshop, so it might be a worker co-op, can be employee owned.

66
00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:20.560
There are also what's called secondary co-ops, where co-ops come together and join another co-op, and that can be a cooperative group.

67
00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:27.320
There are also broader representation, representative co-ops, and they're often called tertiary co-ops.

68
00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:36.400
You can have a mix and match, and that's called a multi-stakeholder co-op, where you might have, for example, workers and consumers on the same co-op.

69
00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:46.140
For example, in Mondragon in Spain, the supermarket there is jointly governed by the workers in the supermarket, but also the people that shop there.

70
00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:54.000
So, we're bringing all this together with a co-operative business model, where people are investing in the co-op.

71
00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:04.880
So, you're creating market power through that, so you can actually start to challenge some other players in the market that may be more unethical or may be ripping off consumers or workers.

72
00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:09.100
You're an owner, coming together to make decisions amongst each other.

73
00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:13.620
You're a community member, so coming together as a community of purpose.

74
00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:23.480
You might be a geographic community where you want to do something about the situation in Bendigo, like Ian, or it might be a community of people with a particular interest.

75
00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:28.360
It might be people, you know, app developers, for example, and they could form a worker co-op.

76
00:07:28.360 --> 00:07:35.420
And lastly, you're a patron and the amount of surplus that's made often can reward your patronage.

77
00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:41.580
So, the more you shop, you might be able to get a dividend, for example, depending on how the co-op is structured.

78
00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:55.820
If you're a worker, if you've been contributing a lot through your labour, rather than negotiating with an external management team, you can actually work this stuff amongst yourselves and distribute some of the surplus in an equitable way.

79
00:07:55.820 --> 00:08:03.420
There are also platform co-operatives, and I think this is really important in the current situation with the coronavirus.

80
00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:19.960
But also more generally, this is a new part of the economy, and there are all of these sort of sharing economy businesses, whether it's Airbnb or other platforms where people offer the work and things like that, Airtasker, those sorts of businesses.

81
00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:34.980
But the funny thing about those businesses is they make profit from people working with each other, providing services to the community, but the actual way they're set up as businesses don't actually include the people who are sharing their assets.

82
00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:43.120
For example, the Uber drivers, they're driving around in their own car, but they're not actually owners of the business.

83
00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:49.940
Similarly with Airbnb, but also Airbnb is starting to think about an ownership stake or an equity stake for some of their members.

84
00:08:49.940 --> 00:09:02.980
But co-ops just take this further and they say, well, if we're going to come together on this business, we're going to be able to actually share decision-making, share reward, and it can actually be a much better situation for those members.

85
00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:30.920
So for example, is Stoxi, which is a co-operative based in the US, but there are some Stoxi photographers in Australia, where stock photographers that take pictures for flyers and advertising and things like that, rather than selling their images to Getty or iStock, they decided to set up their own platform where people could choose to buy beautiful stock photography, and the amount that comes back to the photographer is very, very different.

86
00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:40.920
So those companies that are set up by traditional investor owned company, that a huge amount of that profit goes back to investors.

87
00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:48.100
Whereas in Stoxi, the stock photographers are the investors, they're the owners, they're the patrons.

88
00:09:48.100 --> 00:09:54.180
This is an old-fashioned word I mentioned before, but they're actually doing the work, so they're patronizing the cooperative.

89
00:09:54.180 --> 00:10:09.300
And they're also a really kind of really interesting brand in terms of they have a lot of diversity in terms of people that are taken photos of, for stock photography, they've got their own design aesthetic, and they're quite impressive in that way.

90
00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:22.920
When we think about co-ops, they sit between a for-profit investor owned company on the one side and a not-for-profit often charitable organisation on the other.

91
00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:29.640
So co-ops are owned and run to benefit members, they're democratic, they require active membership from people.

92
00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:34.700
So when you join a co-op, you need to actually contribute something and you also get something back in return.

93
00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:42.620
Whereas often if you join an association, you might go to the AGM once in a while, but not a lot is actually required from you.

94
00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:54.800
Co-ops require something from members, whether it's shopping there at least a year, it might be very light to actually doing an amount of work each year or working in the cooperative if it's a work in co-op.

95
00:10:54.800 --> 00:11:00.480
So there's various ways of harnessing investment into cooperatives.

96
00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:04.920
But essentially the thing to remember is that co-ops make money to do good stuff.

97
00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:07.280
They're not doing stuff to make money.

98
00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:15.700
Co-ops are not exactly not for profit, although there is a version of a co-op that is very not for profit and its classes are not for profit legally.

99
00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.780
But really more accurately, they're profit minimizing.

100
00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:22.180
The surplus made by a cooperative is to cover costs.

101
00:11:22.180 --> 00:11:35.100
So it's to allow for risk, make provisions for the future and pay back investors if there are any, whether they're internal investors as in members and you can structure things where there's external members.

102
00:11:35.100 --> 00:11:39.380
But it's actually about the surplus going back into the business.

103
00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:45.540
So an example of the stock photographers, any of that surplus is going to go back into marketing, it's going to go back into benefiting members.

104
00:11:45.540 --> 00:11:55.520
There's not this huge extractive need to make lots and lots of profit to external shareholders that may or may not have anything to do with the business at all.

105
00:11:55.520 --> 00:12:05.120
So there are structures globally, but also locally where cooperatives come together, they join together and provide different kinds of enterprises.

106
00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:12.420
For example, there's a group of co-ops in the US called the Evergreen Cooperatives.

107
00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:25.120
They have different cooperative businesses where there's solar, there's green city growers where there are tomatoes and veggies in hot houses and things like that.

108
00:12:25.120 --> 00:12:33.720
There's also a laundry service that's provided to a local hospital in Cleveland where the Evergreen cooperatives work.

109
00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:37.860
What that does is those businesses are able to profit share amongst the workers.

110
00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:51.800
So in the example of the laundry service, those workers invest in their co-op and as that co-op becomes more profitable, the surplus is shared amongst those workers.

111
00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:54.760
But they're also part of a bigger ecosystem.

112
00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:59.380
It's about economic development in the Cleveland area.

113
00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:02.480
We've got something a little bit like the Evergreen Co-op.

114
00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:18.420
So when Earthworker was being designed, it was very much inspired by the Evergreen model, which was also inspired by a co-operative group of co-operatives that I mentioned before, the Mondragon co-operatives in the Basque area, Spain.

115
00:13:18.420 --> 00:13:21.020
So there's two great co-ops.

116
00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:26.460
I'm going to spend much time on this because Sean is here from Earthworker to talk about Earthworker.

117
00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:35.180
But there's Earthworker Energy, which is a renewable energy manufacturing business in the Trove Valley, providing dignified work and solar hot water units.

118
00:13:35.180 --> 00:13:40.000
And I've actually bought a solar hot water unit from Earthworker and it works really, really well.

119
00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.740
And there's also RedGum, which is a highly innovative worker owned cleaning service.

120
00:13:44.740 --> 00:13:47.000
It started in February 2018.

121
00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.100
It's got gangbusters.

122
00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:51.480
It's got over 50 regular clients.

123
00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:59.860
All the employee owners in RedGum work casually two to four days a week, and they're working to transition towards permanent part-time employment.

124
00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:08.960
But of course, like every business at the moment, everyone's sort of having a look and going, oh gosh, you know, cleaning business, anything in this current environment, how is that going to work?

125
00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:11.700
But they've been really successful.

126
00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:16.840
They've also won the Employee Ownership Australia Small to Medium Enterprise Award in 2018.

127
00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:28.160
So the way EarthWorker is structured is each EarthWorker worker co-operative is a distributing co-operative where there's ability to profit share amongst the worker members.

128
00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:39.960
EarthWorker itself has as members these worker co-operatives, is a member organisation, is based on co-operative values and principles, and it is a non-distributing co-operative.

129
00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:41.300
Essentially, it's a not-for-profit.

130
00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:50.980
So it's kind of the co-operative commonwealth of these various worker co-op, RedGun and EarthWorker Energy being the first two big ones.

131
00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:56.820
Also allows for member organisations, community organisations that are member-based and democratic.

132
00:14:56.820 --> 00:15:06.760
Then there's Beehive, which is not only looking to transform a sharing economy in Bendigo, but is also looking to transform the economy of Australia.

133
00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:07.860
And dare I say it in the world?

134
00:15:07.860 --> 00:15:11.400
And we've got Ian here, so I'm not going to steal any of his thunder.

135
00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:17.820
So, I think I was going to talk about some of the challenges with co-ops.

136
00:15:17.820 --> 00:15:26.600
Look, there can be challenges where people join a co-op and they just use it here and there where they're not really patronising it regularly.

137
00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:37.240
So, you know, sometimes I get a better deal with a co-op or a member of, but if I can find a better deal somewhere else or I work somewhere else for a while, you know, those sorts of things can be a problem in terms of free riders.

138
00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:42.880
Sometimes there's conflict between members about the short-term and long-term vision.

139
00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:48.400
Sometimes, because there's not a share price, sometimes it's a bit difficult to find out how is this business going.

140
00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:57.100
So there's a need to actually put in ways of really valuing member input in terms of how the business is going for them.

141
00:15:57.100 --> 00:15:59.660
So there are some challenges as well with co-ops.

142
00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:10.200
To establish a co-op, you just need a minimum of five people and you adopt some rules to work out how the members are going to work with each other.

143
00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:18.420
You often then do a formation statement where you're talking about the financials and the prospective members, what they're getting into.

144
00:16:18.420 --> 00:16:22.240
You only need that for certain types of co-ops, so it's good to have anyway.

145
00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:24.680
Then there's a registrar of cooperatives.

146
00:16:24.680 --> 00:16:31.000
Consumer Affairs Victoria is the one here, but there's similar bodies all across Australia.

147
00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:37.320
And there is cooperative national law with everyone but Queensland being part of this big framework, a common legal framework.

148
00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:41.540
In Queensland, it looks like they're kind of just about to come into cooperative national law.

149
00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:46.020
Then you come together, you approve your rules and you get a.coop address.

150
00:16:46.020 --> 00:16:52.220
And then you can, if this has inspired you at all, you can get out there and start a co-op.

151
00:16:52.220 --> 00:17:01.220
And there's a great website called Get Mutual, Get Mutual.coop, which has lots of great information about investment and how to set up a cooperative.

152
00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:10.740
And it's also got a rules builder where you can just get online and have a legal, legally compliant set of rules, your constitution to your cooperative.

153
00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:13.119
It's also lots of great organizations out there.

154
00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:20.640
Employee Ownership Australia, some great stuff with the Co-op, the Business Council of Co-operatives and Mutuals, the peak in Australia is fantastic.

155
00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:29.120
Co-operative powers, and you, you know, if you want to switch your power from some of the big profit making companies, you can join the Co-operative Power.

156
00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:29.640
It's a great one.

157
00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:31.000
I've just done that recently.

158
00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:37.840
And yeah, there's some great co-ops like Oricup as well, which is an investment co-op for organic farmers.

159
00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:40.520
So there's plenty of people out there.

160
00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:46.840
And there's also, of course, Co-operative Bonds, which I'm a member of and we help people start up co-ops.

161
00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:49.380
So that's my presentation.

162
00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:58.680
I think I've spoken enough, hoping that we can throw over to our panel members, which is Sean and Ian, and then we can open up to some questions.

163
00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:04.140
Well, I think it's over to Sean and Ian now.

164
00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:12.740
So perhaps Sean is a member of Earthworker Co-operative, which was mentioned briefly before in my presentation.

165
00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:18.860
He's a member of the Red Gum Cleaning Co-op Board, which we talked about a little bit before.

166
00:18:19.180 --> 00:18:23.840
He's been involved with Earthworker for six years in a range of fields.

167
00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:33.860
And like all Earthworkers, he's driven by a strong belief in the importance of a collaborative economy to foster a more holistic and inclusive democracy.

168
00:18:33.860 --> 00:18:35.940
So over to you, Sean.

169
00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:36.620
All right.

170
00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:38.860
Just unmuting myself.

171
00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:50.220
Yeah, my relevant background is I was in a community centre for a number of years, for four years that I helped run in Thornbury.

172
00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:56.320
It was kind of an autonomous community centre which ran all kinds of events from underage youth gigs.

173
00:18:56.320 --> 00:19:01.220
We had a big library, bike workshop, meeting space, straight kitchen.

174
00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:29.540
I worked for a year as a coordinator at the Melbourne University Food Co-op at Melbourne Uni and began working with Earthworker about six years ago because it kind of appealed to me as a solution or a response to the climate crisis which brought together economy and environment which there's always been a big gap in for people that care about people having dignified livelihoods and also care about what we're doing to the planet.

175
00:19:29.540 --> 00:19:38.620
And as part of that, I'm on the one of the, as Antony mentioned, I'm a non-member director on the Red Gum Board.

176
00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:40.740
Been doing that for the last two years.

177
00:19:40.740 --> 00:19:44.880
One of the things I'll mention about Red Gum, Antony explained a little bit of how a co-op set up.

178
00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:50.600
They had five people, they worked out a business plan, they made their rules, they got registered.

179
00:19:50.600 --> 00:20:02.320
But the day-to-day working of Red Gum as a co-operative, I think is interesting because it can kind of explain the nuts and bolts of a co-operative rather than this broader level thing.

180
00:20:02.320 --> 00:20:08.300
So the initial five members were all on the board, as well as myself, lawyer, as outside representatives.

181
00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:23.660
So right from the start, these people who are all cleaners took board positions, people took finance positions, secretary, we've had someone be, we've had a couple of people with delegates to the unions, and those positions have swapped over over that time, so people get experience in different roles.

182
00:20:23.660 --> 00:20:32.180
We try as much as we can to have the members educated about the finance side of it, so it's all clear to everyone what's going on and how the finances are working, what the co-op can do.

183
00:20:32.180 --> 00:20:43.480
In those two years since I've been involved, the co-op has grown from five members and probably at its peak was employing about 12 and a couple of those are just left to go and do other work.

184
00:20:43.480 --> 00:21:08.740
Yeah, and so Red Gum grew out of Earthworker, which actually explained a little bit about probably fits under the category of a co-op group or a multi-stakeholder cooperative, though, as with a lot of things with Earthworker, we're a bit ass-backwards when it wasn't a group of co-operatives came together to build this kind of overlaying co-operative structure.

185
00:21:08.740 --> 00:21:13.320
We've kind of done it the other way around, which is an interesting way to do it.

186
00:21:13.320 --> 00:21:22.700
Now, our aim is to kind of build up co-operatives to help enable a just transition away from an extractive economy.

187
00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:30.620
And yeah, I don't have any particular experience in co-operatives or training.

188
00:21:30.620 --> 00:21:35.100
I guess I'm just very interested in collaborating with other people to help meet our needs.

189
00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:45.760
So what that has meant with Earthworker is that as part of the project, I have done whatever I've seen fit that needed doing to make the co-op function.

190
00:21:45.760 --> 00:22:00.080
So that's meant everything from fundraising and crowdfunding drives, currently helping to build the website, even though that's not really my thing, helping to write policy, manning stalls, learning far too much about hot water systems.

191
00:22:00.080 --> 00:22:05.940
We have the factory in Morewell, which makes hot water systems.

192
00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:18.840
One of the things about that, the factory in Morewell was intended to be kind of easy, intended to be a flagship project, which is in a very economically distressed area, which is also very dependent on coal fired power.

193
00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:34.120
So, that project is intended to demonstrate that we can have dignified well-paid jobs that contribute something to society, and they're also helping to move us away from more carbon dependent forms of life.

194
00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:37.740
Yeah, one of the other, I don't have a presentation, so I'm not going to talk for too long.

195
00:22:37.740 --> 00:22:46.780
One of the other things I'll just say that we were talking about at the start of this meeting, because we noted that there was a bit of a boys club, two of the main founders of Red Gum, both women weren't able to be here tonight.

196
00:22:46.940 --> 00:22:50.660
So I'm kind of, Antony asked me here and there instead.

197
00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:52.300
I just wanted to note that.

198
00:22:52.300 --> 00:22:59.320
And just maybe to talk, just mention a couple of the people that I've been thinking about that have really influenced my thinking around a lot of this stuff.

199
00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:04.360
One of them is Mule Leydemann-Ukeleys, which is a very difficult name to remember.

200
00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:10.180
But if anyone wants to look up the Maintenance Art Manifesto, I highly recommend that.

201
00:23:10.180 --> 00:23:24.520
She is an artist whose practice revolved around helping people to see art as work and especially women's work and care work, maintenance work as work, rather than just this optional add-on.

202
00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:40.380
She was the artist in residence of the New York Sanitation Department from the 1970s onwards, trying to draw attention to all the work that the New York City Sanitation Department did without which the city would collapse, basically, that required society to run.

203
00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:52.880
And I think we're really seeing that now with the coronavirus and the most exploited and disposable workers turn out, actually, to be some of the most important workers that we really can't do without.

204
00:23:52.880 --> 00:24:09.980
One of the other people that I'm thinking of is Stephanie Kelton, who is an economist in the US, who is an advisor to Bernie Sanders, involved with modern monetary theory and has written stuff about economies of care, so caring for communities, caring for people and caring for the planet.

205
00:24:09.980 --> 00:24:11.300
I think that's really good work.

206
00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:22.900
The other person would be Thea Ria-Francos, who has this really great encapsulation of decarbonize, democratize and decommodify.

207
00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:28.640
That's talking about the energy systems and the way we need to transition to be able to deal with climate change.

208
00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:32.660
But I think that applies to the economy more generally.

209
00:24:32.660 --> 00:24:39.360
Decarbonize, democratize the economy and decommodify basic needs for everybody as well.

210
00:24:40.420 --> 00:24:45.640
I think Ian's gone off camera, so maybe I'll, if that's correct.

211
00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:47.020
Alright, Ian's back.

212
00:24:47.020 --> 00:24:48.840
Yeah, maybe I'll leave it there.

213
00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:50.140
Have you talked about other things?

214
00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:53.300
I've probably got a lot more I could say, but hand over to Ian.

215
00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:54.720
Okay, thank you, Sean.

216
00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:56.220
Can everyone hear me?

217
00:24:56.220 --> 00:24:57.040
Beautiful.

218
00:24:57.040 --> 00:24:58.040
Sorry, Sean.

219
00:24:58.040 --> 00:25:06.880
I had to run off camera because my son is watching Frozen in the next room, and I could hear Let It Go being broadcast through the house.

220
00:25:08.200 --> 00:25:11.760
So I very quickly gave him some headphones.

221
00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:15.320
Thanks for organizing this, folks.

222
00:25:15.640 --> 00:25:23.060
I think the best way for me to explain Beehive, and we are a very proud cooperative.

223
00:25:23.060 --> 00:25:32.620
It's always good to hear Antony do the Co-operative 101 and to fire up again about why cooperatives are so important.

224
00:25:33.080 --> 00:25:51.320
I have been in environmental education and culture change for 20 years, and started with our team at Beehive four years ago, thinking about how we could bring together the ecological and the social and the economic parts of our economy together.

225
00:25:51.320 --> 00:26:05.420
So Beehive is about local people, local place, and local economy, where our vision is that we own our digital sharing economy together, and we're building our first large one.

226
00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:07.020
At the moment, it's called Villages.

227
00:26:07.020 --> 00:26:10.200
It's going to be launched at the end of August.

228
00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:14.480
And Villages is geographic in nature.

229
00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:22.840
At the center of Beehive, people will be a member of their village in their local community with people who live within two kilometers of them.

230
00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:28.520
They will be able to share access to free goods and services, free stuff, free skills.

231
00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:31.560
They will be able to share posts and ask for things.

232
00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:33.300
They will be able to direct message each other.

233
00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:34.880
They will be able to plan things together.

234
00:26:34.880 --> 00:26:37.040
They will be able to set up events together.

235
00:26:38.060 --> 00:26:43.640
Beehive is a non-distributing cooperative, as Antony was talking about before.

236
00:26:43.640 --> 00:26:50.580
So that means if it makes a profit, it just puts that money back into the local community and into improving the platform.

237
00:26:50.580 --> 00:27:07.200
When you become a member of Beehive, which is starting in Bendigo, you own Beehive, you own your data, you own the platform, no one will advertise at you, no one will sell your data to anyone, and you can build community around you.

238
00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:14.460
We have, it's interesting the terminology we use at Beehive, we've always talked about getting an epidemic of belonging.

239
00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:23.280
And I think since at the moment we've got an epidemic that's creating social isolation, you can understand what I'm talking about there.

240
00:27:23.280 --> 00:27:29.460
So we want to connect people together in their local place, and we want that to be at the center of their local economy.

241
00:27:29.460 --> 00:27:34.300
Now that's at the very local geographic phase around your house.

242
00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:42.440
Around that, we're helping to enable and set up distributing cooperatives in the sharing economy in Bendigo.

243
00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:45.300
So the first one we're working on is car sharing.

244
00:27:45.300 --> 00:27:50.480
So we're working with a group of businesses in Bendigo to set up a car sharing cooperative.

245
00:27:50.480 --> 00:27:57.800
It will be a member of Beehive Co-operative, and people will access cars and car sharing through their village.

246
00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:04.940
So when we've set up car sharing and when we've set up villages, they kind of lock in together.

247
00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:13.700
So you're in your village and you've got access to all the free sharing community building in your own local community.

248
00:28:13.700 --> 00:28:17.700
And then at the Bendigo or the city scale, there's going to be car sharing.

249
00:28:17.700 --> 00:28:26.400
And it would be good to talk to Earth Worker when we get to that point about getting, you know, the possibility of getting a solar hot water manufacturing Earth Worker in Bendigo.

250
00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:29.180
That's a member of the Beehive Co-operative in Bendigo.

251
00:28:29.180 --> 00:28:35.620
We want to do redo the economy from the ground up, starting in Bendigo to the city scale.

252
00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:47.620
So when you're thinking about participatory democracy, we could end up with a platform that has, I don't know, 5000, 10,000, 20,000, 30,000 members in Bendigo.

253
00:28:47.620 --> 00:28:51.040
And everyone is connected with their community.

254
00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:54.540
They're sharing access to goods and services with their community.

255
00:28:54.540 --> 00:29:03.540
They've got paid sharing enterprises that are operating in their city that are enabling them to access goods and services rather than owning them.

256
00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:16.600
So the plan eventually is that we'd be like an incubator locally and we could set up energy and water and food and monetary cooperatives locally that all benefit the Bendigo economy.

257
00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:27.800
We've got two and a half billion dollars spent by Bendigo households every year on goods and services and most of that leaves Bendigo and most of that leaves the country.

258
00:29:27.800 --> 00:29:37.680
So what we want to do is localise that spend and localise meaningful work and localise ownership of the economy.

259
00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:47.440
And with the sharing economy, because it's an access economy rather than ownership, you should be saving money on goods and services locally too.

260
00:29:47.800 --> 00:29:52.460
Our idea about scale is quite simple.

261
00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:59.880
We want to grow the Beehive Co-operative to the size of the Bendigo economy, and then it doesn't need to grow anymore.

262
00:29:59.880 --> 00:30:14.120
And we want to partner with other local places, other local towns, other local cities, who want to replicate the model and keep their spending and ownership and work local as well.

263
00:30:14.120 --> 00:30:31.580
So other places that want to replicate, it would be, you know, instead of scaling like a startup and taking over the world, we want Beehive to build from local place to local place, and each local place to own their own local economy.

264
00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:32.940
That's probably enough, I think.

265
00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:40.240
I could go on and on and on about Beehive, and I have been for years, but it would be good to answer some people's questions that they might have.

266
00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:43.600
Thank you so much.

267
00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:46.500
That was great introduction.

268
00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:52.740
Before we move on, I was just wondering localized, so you definitely know about localized, Ian, don't you?

269
00:30:52.740 --> 00:30:53.420
Yeah.

270
00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:54.160
Yeah, awesome.

271
00:30:54.160 --> 00:31:00.240
I know that as well because that's very inspiring for me too, and I believe it's very related to what we're talking about here.

272
00:31:01.400 --> 00:31:01.720
Yeah.

273
00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:07.800
Localized is large business or small business, and it's also not a cooperative.

274
00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:18.740
I know 3O well and I love what they're doing, but we're talking about peer-to-peer or cooperatives providing services to people in local communities rather than business-to-business.

275
00:31:18.740 --> 00:31:22.640
But yeah, they're doing some great work at localized.

276
00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:27.740
In terms of creating networks, very resilient networks and communities that's related.

277
00:31:27.740 --> 00:31:34.760
But that's interesting angle as well, which they're not a cooperative, but these things like that could potentially use cooperative structure.

278
00:31:34.760 --> 00:31:38.620
That would be my question when it gets to question and answer, possibly for Antony.

279
00:31:38.620 --> 00:31:39.620
So let's start with that.

280
00:31:39.620 --> 00:31:41.660
We had Andrew Downing.

281
00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:48.560
Andrew was asking non-member directors.

282
00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:52.080
So Antony, do you want to answer that?

283
00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:57.620
Well, I could, but Sean is actually a non-member director, so I might throw it over to him.

284
00:31:58.160 --> 00:32:00.840
I'm happy to talk about that as well.

285
00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:05.420
Sure, I'll try and talk to that.

286
00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:16.680
Please correct me if I'm wrong, Antony, because my learning about what it means to be on a board and what the function of a board actually is comes from my experience with Red Gum.

287
00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:25.060
I haven't had any specific training in that, but my understanding of the way that the board was set up with Red Gum is that there's five member directors.

288
00:32:25.060 --> 00:32:26.260
So they're all worker members.

289
00:32:26.380 --> 00:32:29.660
They all work in the co-op and they're all on the board.

290
00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:39.420
And there was two positions in our rules for non-member directors to bring both outside expertise that the co-op didn't have internally.

291
00:32:39.420 --> 00:32:48.320
So our first non-member director was a lawyer and myself representing Earthworker Co-operative as Red Gum was a member of the Earthworker Co-operative Network.

292
00:32:48.320 --> 00:33:08.300
And because I've been with Earthworker for five years and knew a number of the people in Red Gum as a kind of out consultant, I guess I see it as like Ford has a particular responsibility, like mainly legally, their responsibility seems to rest around like kind of financial decision making, making sure that the co-op can meet all its expenses.

293
00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:11.740
So I'm getting, is someone, you can speak it rather than the headphones.

294
00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:14.480
If everyone can mute, I think that's a good idea.

295
00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:15.300
Yeah, maybe muting.

296
00:33:15.300 --> 00:33:17.480
I'm just getting a lot of feedback of my own voice.

297
00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:19.360
Yeah, so I feel like I'm rambling a bit.

298
00:33:21.760 --> 00:33:24.600
The member directors kind of represent the membership.

299
00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:36.260
And so my position on the board is not to, I don't feel it's like to contradict, it's just to bring the expertise and kind of go with whatever the membership thinks is the best decision around things.

300
00:33:36.260 --> 00:33:42.720
As long as it kind of, as long as we can get to a point where we can agree that it's the best position for the co-op to be in.

301
00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:44.840
If you have more thoughts on that, Antony.

302
00:33:45.960 --> 00:33:47.380
I think you described that really well.

303
00:33:47.560 --> 00:33:54.160
The only thing that I just sort of add to sort of compliment what you're saying is that co-operatives are member-driven.

304
00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:57.320
It's about member democracy.

305
00:33:57.320 --> 00:34:00.120
But a board has this broad responsibility.

306
00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:05.700
So sometimes there's a need to bring in someone external that has a particular expertise.

307
00:34:05.700 --> 00:34:10.159
It might be law, it could be marketing, it could be any of those sorts of things.

308
00:34:10.159 --> 00:34:13.600
So you can bring someone on board literally to do that.

309
00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:17.400
And non-member directors always have to be in the minority.

310
00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:24.780
So all the decisions that are made by a cooperative at the board level need to be made through member majority decision making.

311
00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:32.380
However, the non-member director does have a vote, just in the minority to protect and safeguard that member democracy.

312
00:34:32.380 --> 00:34:37.300
Maybe we can move on to the other question unless anyone has questions about that, those answers.

313
00:34:37.300 --> 00:34:45.699
We have a question by Anouk and he basically said, Hi, Ayn, you've been at Beehive for a while now.

314
00:34:45.699 --> 00:34:47.480
What challenges has surprised you?

315
00:34:47.480 --> 00:35:00.160
And if I've just lost my job and have been inspired by the cooperatives that we discussed today, what would I wish to that I wouldn't have known in two years time if I dived in setting up a cooperative here in Melbourne?

316
00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:05.320
Yeah, okay, yeah.

317
00:35:05.320 --> 00:35:09.800
So setting up Beehive Co-operative has been quite hard.

318
00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:14.360
You know, you need five promoters to set up a cooperative.

319
00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:23.880
And my first piece of advice would be to get together with five other fired up people, work with you on setting up your cooperative.

320
00:35:23.880 --> 00:35:27.600
There is a network of brilliant people around Australia who can help.

321
00:35:27.960 --> 00:35:34.340
And that is much more established, in my opinion, than it was five years ago when we started thinking about Beehive.

322
00:35:34.340 --> 00:35:40.500
So make sure that you get help from the great people that are out there that really do understand cooperatives.

323
00:35:40.500 --> 00:35:45.280
There is also movements around the world that have really great people.

324
00:35:45.280 --> 00:35:49.720
Platform Co-operatives movement globally has given us a lot of ideas and a lot of help.

325
00:35:49.720 --> 00:36:03.180
But I would actually say the more cooperatives that we have around the country, the more we are going to be able to pull our thinking in an open source kind of way and help each other local place out.

326
00:36:03.180 --> 00:36:14.280
So I would say talk to current cooperatives and see if you can replicate what they are doing because we have got some really, really great organizations and people out there that have already done all the hard work.

327
00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:25.040
So with Beehive, what we are saying is we would love to talk to other people from other places that would like to replicate our model and we would like to help them do that.

328
00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:34.100
So I would say talk to people that have done a lot of hard work and see if you can replicate rather than trying to start from scratch.

329
00:36:34.100 --> 00:36:37.080
Capital raising has been really, really, really hard.

330
00:36:37.080 --> 00:36:41.040
We have done five years of hard yards there and we still don't have an answer.

331
00:36:41.780 --> 00:36:51.700
What we have done to this point is raise enough capital to finish our car sharing business model, which is now looking good, and to build our central application, Villagers.

332
00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:53.400
So that will be launched in August.

333
00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:56.580
But we're still volunteer board members that are running Beehive.

334
00:36:57.180 --> 00:37:03.540
We want to move to a point where we've got a highly successful cooperative that's employing lots of people.

335
00:37:03.540 --> 00:37:07.380
Hopefully with Villagers that we start to turn that corner.

336
00:37:07.380 --> 00:37:17.680
But capital raising as a cooperative is quite hard, especially when you're trying to raise capital for a digital platform that, you know, it needs capital to build that platform.

337
00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:22.960
So I would say reach out and network and find good ideas.

338
00:37:22.960 --> 00:37:28.540
And one of the cooperative principles is that cooperatives cooperate with other cooperatives.

339
00:37:28.540 --> 00:37:41.980
So reach out and see what's there and look at your skill set and look at the great cooperatives that are already in existence and get in touch and say, you know, how can we replicate?

340
00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:57.720
If I could just add to that, Ian, the actual the the ability for both external investors and internal member investors, it's able to be done.

341
00:37:57.740 --> 00:38:13.940
One of the challenges that we face, and I'd be interested to hear from participants if they have any comments about this, one of the challenges that we face is that cooperative shares operate, you know, that members have, operate differently from shares on the stock market.

342
00:38:13.940 --> 00:38:17.460
So they don't fluctuate in price, they're fixed value.

343
00:38:17.460 --> 00:38:24.120
So when you leave, you know, it can be a bit of a delay, but generally when you leave the co-op, you get your money back from your shares.

344
00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:45.080
There's also this thing called cooperative capital units, where external investors who aren't members, you don't have control in terms of how much money they put into the cooperative, but they like the cooperative, they think it's got a good business plan, it's going to be viable, and there's a social return on this co-op going well, and there's also going to be a financial return.

345
00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:50.980
That's there as well, but the problem we have is that no one's heard of a cooperative capital unit.

346
00:38:50.980 --> 00:38:55.380
Those that have heard of it are a bit scared of it because it sounds different.

347
00:38:56.640 --> 00:39:02.980
Also, it does turn off some investors because some investors are very concerned about having control.

348
00:39:02.980 --> 00:39:03.920
There's some challenges.

349
00:39:04.020 --> 00:39:07.520
I reckon we can get the investment from the community.

350
00:39:07.520 --> 00:39:14.280
In some ways, it's about actually communicating that value in a way that's going to be effective.

351
00:39:14.280 --> 00:39:16.060
That nut's yet to be cracked, I reckon.

352
00:39:17.180 --> 00:39:36.720
I'll just add to that, too, Antony, that we will find that out very quickly once we have our villagers' platform and we haven't was on board, because at the moment, we've got this gap where people aren't going to invest in something they can't see and touch and hold.

353
00:39:36.720 --> 00:39:51.400
So hopefully, we'll have a bit of an answer from at least Indigo from August onwards about people seeing the value of being involved in co-op and then and seeing whether they'll invest further in that cooperative thing.

354
00:39:52.800 --> 00:39:53.420
Thank you.

355
00:39:53.920 --> 00:40:01.200
So that was the question to the challenges that Anukh brought up, and we had everyone talking about it.

356
00:40:01.200 --> 00:40:03.320
Apparently, it's an actual big challenge.

357
00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:12.100
I also want to point out that we will collect the links and resources and references and send it to everyone who signed up through different channels.

358
00:40:12.100 --> 00:40:13.360
We've got Meetup.

359
00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:17.640
If you haven't signed up, I'll put the link here, just RSVP, so we can actually send you an email.

360
00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:20.460
If you can't do that, you may not be able to.

361
00:40:20.460 --> 00:40:28.420
I'll put the email to the website, so you can shoot an email so we include you when we send that information regarding the challenges.

362
00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:33.200
Two people brought up the question about job losses.

363
00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:41.780
Nick, one of the organizers of this group, by the way, he asked, how do cooperatives deal with job losses?

364
00:40:42.160 --> 00:40:44.380
This is something that I've been very interested as well.

365
00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:52.420
How can we help as disruption is happening, and workforce find a new place and address?

366
00:40:52.420 --> 00:40:55.440
Yeah, so that would make it very related as Brian is mentioning.

367
00:40:55.440 --> 00:40:58.700
Also, Anouk put it very delicately.

368
00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:04.140
I read out what Anouk has put again, so for the whole panel, if they have an answer.

369
00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:17.100
Anouk says, if I've just lost my job and have been inspired by this discussion today, what would I wish I'd known in two years time if I dive into setting up a cooperative here in Melbourne?

370
00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:17.900
That's very interesting.

371
00:41:17.900 --> 00:41:23.940
Or maybe how can someone discover if there's probably people who are thinking like this?

372
00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:24.760
How can you discover?

373
00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:27.140
So that's something that I'm adding to the whole mix.

374
00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:28.860
Who wants to speak first?

375
00:41:28.860 --> 00:41:30.960
What was the last part of that question?

376
00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:32.880
I think Sean was just asking, Alexar.

377
00:41:34.600 --> 00:41:40.960
All right, maybe I just want to say something about the question of what would you wish you'd known in two years?

378
00:41:40.960 --> 00:42:00.260
And this is partly triggered by Ian saying something about the model of Silicon Valley and startups, which that phrase of move fast and break things, that I think if you're thinking like a cooperative, ideally, and in this current moment, is move slow and repair things.

379
00:42:00.960 --> 00:42:06.500
And by move slowly, I don't mean, I mean kind of in a systematic way.

380
00:42:06.500 --> 00:42:08.020
Like you've got to think long term.

381
00:42:08.020 --> 00:42:13.780
You're going to want to be doing work all the time towards the cooperative if you're trying to set up.

382
00:42:13.780 --> 00:42:17.120
I also think the other thing to think about is like what's your niche?

383
00:42:17.120 --> 00:42:18.440
What niche can you fill?

384
00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:19.340
Because that's really important.

385
00:42:19.340 --> 00:42:24.960
You've got to have a business case for it because we're operating in a capitalist system.

386
00:42:24.960 --> 00:42:29.020
And if you're trying to compete at that level, you're just going to get crushed.

387
00:42:29.240 --> 00:42:31.520
And lastly, it's all about the people.

388
00:42:31.520 --> 00:42:32.860
You've got to have good people.

389
00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:42.940
It's absolutely core if the people that you're working with aren't committed to a project, aren't committed to each other and the relationships are going to collapse.

390
00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:49.840
One thing that I'd say is adding to what you're saying, Sean, is that where are the needs?

391
00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:54.040
And in particular, in this time of crisis, there will be plenty of needs.

392
00:42:55.260 --> 00:43:08.080
And one thing a co-operative can do is it can get going, it can get members support from people that can, like crowdfunding, you're not looking for one big huge investor.

393
00:43:08.080 --> 00:43:12.780
You're looking for lots and lots of small investments and opportunities.

394
00:43:12.780 --> 00:43:18.160
We're probably heading towards a recession, possibly even a depression.

395
00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:27.320
I hate to think that, but we're certainly heading towards a recession because of what has happened with climate change, what's happened with the bushfires.

396
00:43:27.320 --> 00:43:34.020
And then secondly, the whole economy is being, is growing to a sort of a standstill.

397
00:43:35.180 --> 00:43:37.580
A standstill, is that the right word?

398
00:43:37.580 --> 00:43:43.560
So there'll be plenty of opportunities for communities to come together and go, let's work with what we've got.

399
00:43:43.720 --> 00:43:49.160
I mentioned Mondragon, the area of the Basque region of Spain.

400
00:43:49.160 --> 00:43:56.640
And that cooperative is a massive, that group of cooperatives is quite a massive for its population.

401
00:43:56.640 --> 00:43:58.560
About 70,000 employees.

402
00:43:58.560 --> 00:44:03.660
It's the seventh largest company type group in Spain.

403
00:44:03.660 --> 00:44:05.480
The scale is really, really high.

404
00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:11.800
They started directly after the Spanish Civil War, where there was absolute devastation.

405
00:44:12.700 --> 00:44:14.140
And they had nothing.

406
00:44:14.140 --> 00:44:16.400
So they started with education.

407
00:44:16.400 --> 00:44:18.640
Education is really important for cooperatives.

408
00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:23.400
So actually learning about cooperatives, learning about how to work with each other.

409
00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:27.680
So starting with education is probably a good place to start.

410
00:44:27.680 --> 00:44:31.080
Then they found a product that lots and lots of people wanted.

411
00:44:31.080 --> 00:44:33.540
It was a particular kind of heater at the time.

412
00:44:33.540 --> 00:44:36.060
That started to sell like gangbusters.

413
00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:38.920
So they knew how to make that stuff.

414
00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:40.940
And they started making and selling.

415
00:44:41.420 --> 00:44:45.620
And then they started to think about, in a way, an ecosystem of cooperation.

416
00:44:45.620 --> 00:44:59.480
So that whole area is a, you know, there's a cooperative university, there's cooperative finance like the credit unions, there is the worker owned and consumer owned cooperatives there.

417
00:44:59.480 --> 00:45:27.260
So when the global financial crisis hit, when one of those big worker cooperatives went under because of the pressure of what was happening globally, there was enough resources within the ecosystem of Mondragon to allow those workers a living wage for a significant period of time from the cooperative community's own resources and to redeploy most of those worker owners into other parts of Mondragon.

418
00:45:27.260 --> 00:45:50.360
So the networking effect that what Earthworker is trying to achieve, with cooperatives cooperating together, worker cooperatives under the big Earthworker banner and what Beehive is trying to achieve with having lots of cooperatives that join Beehive is really essential because what you're getting a market share, but you're also protect each other if and when things go wrong.

419
00:45:50.360 --> 00:45:56.140
So a piece of advice just lastly would be have a look at what exists out there now.

420
00:45:56.140 --> 00:46:07.680
Earthworker is there now, Beehive is there now, find out what they're doing, learn from them and then maybe be part of them or build something that's complementary to what those other cooperatives are doing.

421
00:46:09.100 --> 00:46:16.640
I would also say there's a lot of great cooperatives overseas that aren't necessarily represented in Australia, but it's worth looking at.

422
00:46:16.640 --> 00:46:19.740
There's cooperatives in every every kind of sector you can imagine.

423
00:46:19.740 --> 00:46:28.260
I can just think about the US, there's bakeries, there's organic grocery stores, window makers.

424
00:46:28.260 --> 00:46:31.980
There's just a whole lot of stuff that we don't necessarily see on the ground here.

425
00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:41.080
So I think it's also worth looking outside of Australia just to see the possibilities and how those other models exist, but also a lot of good resources here if you look.

426
00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:42.200
Thank you.

427
00:46:42.200 --> 00:46:46.320
So this has been a great conversation so far.

428
00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:52.160
So there was a question that I had, if it's related to this conversation, please panel decide.

429
00:46:52.160 --> 00:47:01.200
I've heard of a second tier cooperatives, which I understand it's been cooperatives make a cooperative themselves, but that's as far as I know, I may even be wrong on that.

430
00:47:01.700 --> 00:47:10.700
If that's something that is related to our conversation, please, that would be good if you expand on it.

431
00:47:10.700 --> 00:47:21.400
Well, both Beehive and Earthworker, Earthworker Cooperative and Beehive are designed as second tier kind of cooperatives where cooperatives can join them.

432
00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:30.240
They're both, well, particularly with Earthworker, it's a multi-stakeholder co-op, so other people, people and co-ops can join Earthworker.

433
00:47:30.640 --> 00:47:35.840
So both of them are designed in that way.

434
00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:36.360
Interesting.

435
00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:42.080
So the second tier doesn't imply that in that tier, only cooperatives can join.

436
00:47:42.080 --> 00:47:47.560
So in the same flat level, there are individual members and a cooperative member.

437
00:47:48.660 --> 00:48:01.480
You can have a second tier or a secondary cooperative that is a multi-stakeholder cooperative, so it has different types of members.

438
00:48:01.480 --> 00:48:07.420
If it is just a cooperative of other cooperatives, that's technically what's called a cooperative group.

439
00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:13.760
And it only takes two cooperatives to form a new cooperative, which is a cooperative group.

440
00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:20.280
Why you would do that is that you can share resources, you can market together, you can figure out financial systems.

441
00:48:20.280 --> 00:48:22.540
So you're building infrastructure.

442
00:48:22.540 --> 00:48:32.660
The secondary cooperative is building infrastructure and support for the primary cooperatives, which are front facing and very focused on their businesses.

443
00:48:34.220 --> 00:48:35.000
Thank you, Anthony.

444
00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:42.020
So this was, I believe this answered the other question that I wanted to ask when it was Ian mentioned about localized.

445
00:48:42.040 --> 00:48:56.320
And I thought if there is any business that wants to act as a network weaver, if you know what I mean, certain networks, they want to kind of facilitate transactions or connections to flow between different networks.

446
00:48:56.320 --> 00:49:01.680
It seems to me that cooperative is a really good structure for that.

447
00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:02.600
Are there alternatives?

448
00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:04.040
Is that right assumption?

449
00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:05.380
Are there alternatives to that?

450
00:49:05.380 --> 00:49:17.940
And is there some examples of this particular case when to connect different businesses and cooperatives comes in and connects different industries together or different, basically, you mentioned, geographic locations together.

451
00:49:17.940 --> 00:49:21.900
But you might have mentioned, I may have missed, but I'll leave it to you.

452
00:49:21.900 --> 00:49:26.300
Okay, so I can have a go at that one for starters anyway.

453
00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:35.900
So the way the WebEHUB is going to look at networks, so every member will have their own identity and their own reputation.

454
00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:39.320
That starts in their geographic village.

455
00:49:39.320 --> 00:49:44.280
But that reputation and identity will then go out through the sharing enterprises and back.

456
00:49:44.420 --> 00:49:48.440
So everyone will have one identity and one reputation in their town.

457
00:49:48.440 --> 00:49:52.340
And that will network through all the different cooperatives and back again.

458
00:49:52.340 --> 00:49:58.760
So we're looking at setting up a, it's kind of a network that links all the cooperatives together.

459
00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:05.080
All the cooperatives that use that reputation and identity will be members of the Beehive Cooperative in Bendigo.

460
00:50:05.080 --> 00:50:08.720
So that's creating a network of cooperatives around.

461
00:50:08.720 --> 00:50:20.020
And that's really what Antony was talking about with Mondragon in Spain, that you have a network of cooperatives locally and can help with employment and can share funds around and look after each other.

462
00:50:20.340 --> 00:50:25.500
We're aiming to be like a local incubator for cooperatives in Bendigo.

463
00:50:25.500 --> 00:50:29.720
But then we want to partner, as I said, with others in other places who want to do the same thing.

464
00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:37.940
And there are brilliant ideas out there, across the world in cooperatives that we would love to partner with and create networks.

465
00:50:38.440 --> 00:50:45.340
Our kind of idea is that we have open source ideas and networking between cooperatives.

466
00:50:45.340 --> 00:50:55.860
So if one cooperative in one place has an idea, they just share it with all the other cooperatives in all the other local places, open source.

467
00:50:55.860 --> 00:51:01.040
And that's a way that we can really spread ideas quickly, nationally, globally.

468
00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:03.560
Did that answer your question, Alexar?

469
00:51:03.560 --> 00:51:04.420
It did, actually.

470
00:51:04.420 --> 00:51:07.100
I was wondering if there is any question.

471
00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:10.940
And the question was right in front of us, like on the panel.

472
00:51:10.940 --> 00:51:11.700
That was amazing.

473
00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:14.140
And that was a beautiful architecture.

474
00:51:14.140 --> 00:51:20.960
I enjoyed listening to the way you described the concept, because you're involving identity and reputation as well.

475
00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:27.060
And very, very important, especially if you get it right, fundamentally, it just kind of explodes.

476
00:51:27.060 --> 00:51:32.180
Because these are two areas where there hasn't been a good design, my experience so far.

477
00:51:32.180 --> 00:51:33.540
So we have another question from Nick.

478
00:51:33.740 --> 00:51:38.240
Unless someone else wants, on the panel or in the audience, wants to add to that.

479
00:51:38.240 --> 00:51:38.620
Great.

480
00:51:38.620 --> 00:51:52.840
So yeah, my question was, is there a form of legal liability, or like limited liability corporation, such that if they do get sued or become bankrupt, that the people's personal savings are sort of protected?

481
00:51:52.840 --> 00:52:03.340
Like the design of the corporation, one of the great technologies that enabled our society to function the way it does for better and for worse is the invention of the limited liability corporation.

482
00:52:03.600 --> 00:52:06.720
Is that a similar sort of scenario for cooperatives?

483
00:52:06.720 --> 00:52:09.160
Simple answer to that one is yes.

484
00:52:09.160 --> 00:52:21.660
So there have been models historically of business partnerships where there is liability to individuals, where if something terrible happened, you lose the house.

485
00:52:21.660 --> 00:52:29.920
Now, all of the same limited liability protections, if you can talk about it in that way, are available to cooperatives.

486
00:52:30.560 --> 00:52:39.020
However, the cooperative law does have a lot of crossover with some of the obligations that a large corporation would have.

487
00:52:39.020 --> 00:52:48.280
So if people do the wrong thing, if they're directors, for example, they can certainly be liable, just like any other director of any kind of company.

488
00:52:48.280 --> 00:52:57.220
If you're owing some money to the cooperative, then if it gets wound up, you might be liable to pay back the difference if you're still owing money on shares or something like that.

489
00:52:57.220 --> 00:53:04.120
But otherwise, it's all those benefits, and you refer to it as technology, that's all available within the cooperative form.

490
00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:04.640
Yeah.

491
00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:06.060
Very, very similar.

492
00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:06.800
Yeah.

493
00:53:06.800 --> 00:53:07.180
Sure.

494
00:53:07.180 --> 00:53:08.900
Thanks for that.

495
00:53:08.900 --> 00:53:13.760
Can I just ask a follow-up question of I'm sorry, I came in late, so you might have dealt with this.

496
00:53:13.760 --> 00:53:14.760
I do apologize.

497
00:53:14.760 --> 00:53:23.700
Just because we're a democracy group, I'm wondering what the decision-making process is at the board level, or is that where most of the decisions are made?

498
00:53:23.700 --> 00:53:33.520
When I asked this question about job losses, that's one of the questions I was thinking about, who decides that in the co-operative and what's their decision-making process?

499
00:53:33.520 --> 00:53:35.760
There is a board that's elected by members.

500
00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:39.080
There are majority members, so they represent the members.

501
00:53:39.080 --> 00:53:44.160
There is ability to have a general meeting where all members can come together.

502
00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:47.400
Depending on how you're structured, you could certainly do that electronically.

503
00:53:47.400 --> 00:53:51.840
For a really big decision, you would generally get all the members together.

504
00:53:51.840 --> 00:54:03.100
There are certain decisions that require all the members, not just majority, but over 75% in some cases, for some really big decisions that the cooperative is making.

505
00:54:03.100 --> 00:54:09.280
So it is biased towards democracy, but it does also allow a board to get on and govern.

506
00:54:09.280 --> 00:54:14.220
But with big decisions, it's generally got to get in all the members together.

507
00:54:14.240 --> 00:54:15.300
Okay, sure.

508
00:54:15.300 --> 00:54:16.360
Okay, that makes sense.

509
00:54:16.360 --> 00:54:17.160
Thank you.

510
00:54:17.160 --> 00:54:18.100
Thank you so much.

511
00:54:18.100 --> 00:54:19.320
Conscious of time.

512
00:54:19.320 --> 00:54:24.780
We've got 10 minutes and unless there is any burning question, I want to put out SIP.

513
00:54:24.780 --> 00:54:32.480
So the question is, can Co-ops raise capital from early stage backers by issuing credit for future product services?

514
00:54:32.480 --> 00:54:35.300
I'm hearing similar to what Kickstarter is doing.

515
00:54:35.300 --> 00:54:44.500
Will the usual securities laws, which a lot of blockchain products have also been struggling with that in terms of regulation.

516
00:54:44.500 --> 00:54:48.100
So anyone want to address that question, which is quite technical?

517
00:54:49.780 --> 00:55:00.300
There are a lot of similarities, but just in terms of securities and investment, this is a technical sort of area and so it's always an area we should get advice and dig pretty deep.

518
00:55:00.300 --> 00:55:13.660
But in general, just something that I think would be of interest to people, if members join a cooperative and they are investing themselves in the cooperative, it can be at an early stage.

519
00:55:13.660 --> 00:55:19.520
A lot of the regulatory burden that you would get with a regular company is lessened.

520
00:55:20.180 --> 00:55:28.700
Because the principle is if you're a member and you're able to vote, you're a part of this thing and you're wanting to invest.

521
00:55:28.700 --> 00:55:31.020
There are still things like disclosure statements.

522
00:55:31.020 --> 00:55:38.640
So the cooperative needs to provide really openly and transparently what the offer is, should go into all of the risks.

523
00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:43.380
So it's certainly about making sure those sorts of things are in place.

524
00:55:43.380 --> 00:55:54.500
But it's actually a form of enterprise that marries up quite well to a crowdfunding type of ethos, because you all own it together, you're all investing in it together.

525
00:55:54.500 --> 00:56:00.660
The one difficult part is when a worker cooperative might have 10 workers, and they may not have enough money to really invest in it.

526
00:56:00.660 --> 00:56:14.080
But there is an option to get external investment, the threshold and the things that you need to do to get that external investment is higher, for the same reasons that are in place for other kinds of companies.

527
00:56:14.180 --> 00:56:17.260
So, yeah, it's very nuanced.

528
00:56:17.260 --> 00:56:21.960
It's very horses for courses, but I've just tried to answer that generally.

529
00:56:21.960 --> 00:56:30.880
So as to kind of highlight, there are some greater opportunities with co-op, once people get their heads around it, in terms of harnessing that kind of investment.

530
00:56:30.880 --> 00:56:34.980
But Ian and Sean might have other comments about that as well.

531
00:56:34.980 --> 00:56:38.920
I've been in touch a bit with Kevin Cox from Pre-Pay Solar.

532
00:56:38.920 --> 00:56:45.020
So the question included, can people pre-pay for services as like an investment?

533
00:56:45.020 --> 00:57:02.600
So there is an organization based out of Sydney, Kevin Cox is behind it, and they're looking at getting people to pre-pay for solar power up front, and using that kind of investment, it doesn't kind of interfere with cooperative shares or anything.

534
00:57:02.600 --> 00:57:04.540
People are just pre-paying for products.

535
00:57:04.540 --> 00:57:06.380
So cooperatives can certainly do that.

536
00:57:07.640 --> 00:57:08.000
Thanks.

537
00:57:08.240 --> 00:57:09.660
It's really helpful.

538
00:57:10.900 --> 00:57:14.280
So did we have someone wanting to ask a question?

539
00:57:14.280 --> 00:57:14.540
Okay.

540
00:57:14.540 --> 00:57:15.660
Sid says, thanks.

541
00:57:15.660 --> 00:57:16.920
That's good acknowledgement.

542
00:57:16.920 --> 00:57:18.840
Thank you, Sid.

543
00:57:19.080 --> 00:57:21.220
I think I had someone wanting to ask.

544
00:57:21.220 --> 00:57:24.380
So if that was the case, feel free to continue speaking.

545
00:57:24.380 --> 00:57:27.220
I start basically, the very quick round around the house.

546
00:57:27.700 --> 00:57:35.980
I'm personally thinking of consumers, cooperatives for like very, very small, organic consumer cooperative for the panic buying situation.

547
00:57:35.980 --> 00:57:42.560
And it's not just panic buying, but also very soon, I believe, we need to know exactly how we're distributing the resources.

548
00:57:42.560 --> 00:57:45.540
So I think cooperative structure looks like a good model.

549
00:57:45.540 --> 00:57:46.560
That's where my head is at.

550
00:57:46.560 --> 00:57:51.260
If anyone's got suggestion, wants to work on it, play it on, Brandon Strong, I'd like to hear.

551
00:57:51.260 --> 00:58:05.980
Can I just say, Alexar, that if the last few weeks has taught us anything, it's that casual workers, you know, the extractive for-profit economy, are all two or three weeks away from poverty.

552
00:58:06.520 --> 00:58:10.520
And directors of large corporations are three months away from bankruptcy.

553
00:58:10.520 --> 00:58:13.480
I mean, the global economy is a house of cards.

554
00:58:13.480 --> 00:58:21.880
And we don't have a cooperative network in Australia, we are strong enough to be able to support people through a time like this moment.

555
00:58:21.880 --> 00:58:27.080
But we do have a lot of people working on start-up cooperatives.

556
00:58:27.080 --> 00:58:30.200
You know, Beehive is going to be live in August.

557
00:58:30.220 --> 00:58:31.520
Earthwork is already there.

558
00:58:31.520 --> 00:58:46.800
There's like a whole new movement of 21st century cooperatives that are forming right now that will really, really help with providing money for work, localising ownership, localising spending, getting spending circulating rather than it being extractive.

559
00:58:47.100 --> 00:58:58.920
And it mightn't help us in this moment right now because we're all starting, but hopefully down the track it'll provide a real buffer to the kind of shocks that we're seeing.

560
00:58:58.920 --> 00:59:10.460
And we're seeing a pandemic, but we've got coming economic shocks around climate and around biodiversity and around just the nature of the extractive economy itself.

561
00:59:10.460 --> 00:59:12.700
We need a new system.

562
00:59:12.700 --> 00:59:18.680
I think there's a lot of people in the cooperatives movement that are working really hard on creating that new economy.

563
00:59:18.680 --> 00:59:32.700
So I just wanted to say it, you know, there's a I've probably had 40 emails and phone calls this week from people saying, be hive ready, be hive ready, we need to stop people buying toilet paper and everyone needs to connect with neighbors and we need to do this right now.

564
00:59:33.060 --> 00:59:37.320
And I keep saying, look, it's people are panicked right now.

565
00:59:37.320 --> 00:59:43.540
You know, there's all sorts of wonderful people working on wonderful solutions, but there's a whole movement that is coming, the cooperatives movement.

566
00:59:44.380 --> 00:59:49.200
It's not quite big enough in Australia to make the impact that it will make in the future.

567
00:59:49.200 --> 00:59:49.720
Okay.

568
00:59:49.720 --> 00:59:51.000
Thank you very much.

569
00:59:51.000 --> 01:00:06.380
Some of the things that what you're talking about popped into my mind was about, however, I remember there was GameStop employers essentially being forced by GameStop to still serve even in amidst a, well, essentially a lockdown.

570
01:00:06.380 --> 01:00:08.920
Basically, have you heard about this story?

571
01:00:09.940 --> 01:00:10.060
No.

572
01:00:11.160 --> 01:00:19.020
Well, in America, there's a big coronavirus epidemic going on, and I think today, they actually exceeded Italy.

573
01:00:19.020 --> 01:00:21.280
Andrew, would you like to jump in?

574
01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:22.240
Oh, Andrew, me?

575
01:00:22.240 --> 01:00:22.640
Yes.

576
01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:23.520
Hello.

577
01:00:23.520 --> 01:00:25.540
Yeah.

578
01:00:25.540 --> 01:00:35.600
I don't know how well this whole thing would get received or what I wanted to say, but I noticed a bunch of odd sort of one.

579
01:00:35.600 --> 01:00:46.840
Firstly, I would get to get this across that I'm very much a systems thinker, and I look at this whole discussion in terms of a bunch of very interacting systems and what things would work and why.

580
01:00:46.840 --> 01:00:51.280
And so some strange observations about contradictions I see in all this.

581
01:00:52.120 --> 01:01:03.600
I get a very sort of, let's call it anti-capitalist vibe to the whole movement, which is, I don't know why, but then I hear people having trouble raising capital.

582
01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:04.920
Contradiction right there.

583
01:01:04.920 --> 01:01:13.820
Yeah, I hear anti-amphitizing messages and everybody goes, yeah, but you're just trying to spread a message and you don't want to advertise?

584
01:01:13.840 --> 01:01:26.500
It seems like there's a focus on this being cooperatives versus capitalism instead of actually looking for a way to have more like a cooperative, augmented capitalism.

585
01:01:26.500 --> 01:01:28.180
You already have capitalism.

586
01:01:28.180 --> 01:01:41.440
There's all sorts of places where it breaks around the outsides, and every one of those is an opportunity for cooperation, where you could really make a difference there.

587
01:01:41.440 --> 01:02:00.780
I mean, just some wild examples that stand out to me just from very recent times, as the economy gets worse and we get more focused, more centralized, dominant markets and things like, say, retail, you got Coles and Woolworths versus everybody, and they crush the farmers.

588
01:02:00.780 --> 01:02:01.120
Wow.

589
01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:01.520
Okay.

590
01:02:01.520 --> 01:02:01.900
Hang on.

591
01:02:01.900 --> 01:02:04.300
Look, there's an opportunity.

592
01:02:04.300 --> 01:02:22.740
Some of the best cooperatives that ever existed, as far as I can see, the most stable ones, the ones that always managed to somehow get capital, are ones where there's existing businesses, particularly small businesses that can find a way to cooperate with each other, to create a new market and off they go.

593
01:02:22.740 --> 01:02:24.560
They're doing a cooperative thing.

594
01:02:24.560 --> 01:02:30.680
If you create a cooperative set of consumers to work with them as well, then you've got an opportunity, right?

595
01:02:30.680 --> 01:02:37.520
But it stems out the side of capitalism, not in contradiction or on competition with it.

596
01:02:38.040 --> 01:02:42.160
Yet the vibe that I keep hearing is the opposite of that.

597
01:02:42.160 --> 01:02:46.780
I heard people say things like, what was it, was a phrase like that.

598
01:02:46.780 --> 01:02:52.540
They didn't like the move fast and break things when it moves slow and I think the thing is that.

599
01:02:52.540 --> 01:02:58.980
The whole move fast and break things, that whole saying is about you've got to actually make mistakes to learn.

600
01:02:58.980 --> 01:03:00.780
That's the point of it.

601
01:03:01.800 --> 01:03:11.340
So it's got to ask like, move fast and try things, because that's the point, that's the message is to fix things and you actually have to learn by doing and you break some things, right?

602
01:03:11.440 --> 01:03:14.100
That's why that message existed.

603
01:03:14.100 --> 01:03:27.540
And there's this other thing, early on, one of the key issues that was mentioned as a difficulty in creating cooperatives was this issue about people worry about freeloaders, right?

604
01:03:27.540 --> 01:03:29.160
And you understand why that would be.

605
01:03:29.400 --> 01:03:42.180
The concept of freeloaders in cooperative environments is a trust issue and essentially comes down to the whole people fear the tragedy of the common standard game theory problem, right?

606
01:03:42.180 --> 01:03:46.660
That's because people always fear loss more than potential gain.

607
01:03:46.660 --> 01:03:48.600
So they don't want to lose what they have.

608
01:03:49.380 --> 01:03:57.280
They fear the loss much more than they sort of see the potential for game, which is why everybody is very tentative about moving into these things.

609
01:03:57.380 --> 01:04:07.020
And so you always want to be following this funny principle as a user interaction design thing, the principle of commensurate returns.

610
01:04:07.020 --> 01:04:14.320
This is the sort of idea that when you introduce somebody to a thing, you want to give a smooth ramp into it.

611
01:04:14.320 --> 01:04:28.160
So what you want is that somebody, anybody who is new to these things, you want to arrange that their first experience of it is that they put very little emotional energy in and they get some positive gain out of it.

612
01:04:28.160 --> 01:04:29.540
I got to buy something cheaper.

613
01:04:29.540 --> 01:04:30.900
Oh, that was great.

614
01:04:30.900 --> 01:04:31.200
Wow.

615
01:04:31.200 --> 01:04:31.520
Okay.

616
01:04:31.520 --> 01:04:34.520
Maybe I'll invest more interest in this, right?

617
01:04:34.520 --> 01:04:35.980
That sort of idea.

618
01:04:35.980 --> 01:04:39.660
So and then when they invest more energy into it, and then you can ramp it up.

619
01:04:39.660 --> 01:04:45.220
So you want to always have a nice smooth curve where each time they put in, they get something better out of it.

620
01:04:45.840 --> 01:04:59.340
And it turns out to be easy each time, because that's the only way through the sort of the thicket of this fear that really hard times and so it makes it hard for them to engage.

621
01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:05.000
So yeah, I look at this whole thing and I go like, there's too much to mean.

622
01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:14.960
It seems like separation between the what's out there and falling apart, that we could be leveraging versus trying to make things separate.

623
01:05:15.660 --> 01:05:16.740
Maybe I'm rambling too much.

624
01:05:16.740 --> 01:05:19.660
I'm not sure whether anybody gets what I'm trying to say here.

625
01:05:19.660 --> 01:05:42.480
I think there's a lot more potential here in sort of cooperation around, particularly around the falling apart parts of capitalism, where anybody who's on the outer of that who's being squeezed out by monopolistic behaviors is usually somebody who has something to lose that could actually benefit by cooperation, right?

626
01:05:42.480 --> 01:05:44.060
Those are the people you should be creaming up with this.

627
01:05:46.260 --> 01:05:47.280
Thank you very much.

628
01:05:47.280 --> 01:05:50.800
As I understand, with any crisis, there's opportunity.

629
01:05:50.800 --> 01:06:06.160
And the coronavirus epidemic, the bushfire and many crises, what they do is they help bring to light certain structural flaws in society that ultimately by overcoming these problems, we become stronger as a society.

630
01:06:06.160 --> 01:06:10.220
Is that what I understand from talking to you?

631
01:06:10.500 --> 01:06:15.040
If I could just respond as briefly as possible.

632
01:06:15.040 --> 01:06:26.700
Within the cooperative movement, there is certainly a diversity of people that in some ways be described as socialists or others that would be described as being more conservative.

633
01:06:26.700 --> 01:06:33.640
When we're looking at, for example, rural communities, the National Party in Australia is very, very supportive of cooperatives.

634
01:06:33.640 --> 01:06:38.300
We're also getting lots of interest from the union movement in the building of cooperatives.

635
01:06:39.120 --> 01:06:41.160
Certainly, there's always been a tension.

636
01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:47.900
This tension is in the social enterprise movement, but it was also historically been a tension within the cooperative movement.

637
01:06:47.900 --> 01:07:03.880
That if the market is what's normal, then cooperatives can come in and deal where there are market failures, where something's gone wrong, but the market as it's set up is fine, but there's going to be a failure, so the co-op comes in to fix those problems.

638
01:07:04.880 --> 01:07:09.240
And that has historically worked quite well.

639
01:07:09.240 --> 01:07:14.660
It's been a tension between that and people that believe in a broader, more transformative movement.

640
01:07:14.660 --> 01:07:17.520
It used to be called the cooperative commonwealth.

641
01:07:17.520 --> 01:07:25.220
So you've kind of got this idea where perhaps one day, most of our economy will be democratic and participatory.

642
01:07:25.940 --> 01:07:32.700
But you know what, a lot of those people with those different perspectives still work together in the cooperative movement for the common good.

643
01:07:32.700 --> 01:07:37.720
But I don't think we're able, personally, I wouldn't be able to resolve that tension there.

644
01:07:37.720 --> 01:07:48.940
I think it's not only present in the cooperative movement, that tension between and views about capitalism are present in lots of other areas in economic life.

645
01:07:48.940 --> 01:07:59.420
And I think when we're heading towards this sort of crisis where we're talking about things like stopping evictions and those kinds of measures, the whole system is under stress at the moment.

646
01:07:59.420 --> 01:08:04.900
So I guess we need to be thinking about what kind of economy that would like in the future.

647
01:08:06.720 --> 01:08:21.560
Thanks for reaching to this end of the discussion, where Alexis thanked everybody and all the contributors for contributing to this free flowing kind of discussion, which he quite liked because it allows for hearing different kinds of opinions and answer.

648
01:08:21.800 --> 01:08:37.380
And it's also how we all would learn the general structure of how Designing Open Democracy as an organization will function this year is we'd be aiming to have a talk on one month and then an offline discussion on the other month.

649
01:08:37.380 --> 01:08:55.800
And we think this is quite valuable, as in it would allow everybody to have the ability to learn a new concept, then synthesize it and see how we'll apply in their own context, which for our organization will be how do you apply, say, co-operatives in the Australian context.

650
01:08:55.800 --> 01:09:02.760
And I hope you'll be able to have a workshop in your country as well, where you can explore these kinds of concepts as well.

651
01:09:02.760 --> 01:09:21.200
You can also join our online discussion at discuss.designingopendemocracy.com And if you would like to contribute to any of our future talk or give us a tip, then you could also email us at contact at designingopendemocracy.com I hope you enjoyed all our talk so far.

652
01:09:21.200 --> 01:09:32.760
And if you haven't, definitely check out our latest episode with Nicholas Grone from Lateral Economics where we talked and discussed about the concept of citizen juries as well.

653
01:09:32.760 --> 01:09:38.220
So thank you for spending your time to listen to this episode and I hope you learned something new.

654
01:09:38.220 --> 01:09:39.420
See you on the next episode.